No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian Parliament today refused to accept an amendment to the Criminal Code to abolish those paragraphs on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been sentenced.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the liberation of the detainees, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the request to alleviate penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding an allegedly adverse agreement with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final and the verdict is due to be heard before the court in December.
Timoshenko himself called the verdict political revenge of the regime, and also in the West the trial raised the suspicion of prejudice of the court.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the prime minister was sentenced, from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 deputies.
226 votes would have been necessary for his acceptance.
