The menu of a fatty child: It does not breakfast and eats sausage for dinner
More than a third of children from 9 to 13 have obesity problems, with 9 percent of all pupils and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children are mostly from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the milieu in which he grows up and is the examples that surround him is for the healthy development of a person.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are on the table up to half more often than in families with normal children.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had on the day before the reconnaissance campaign under the motto "Obesity is not a coincidence" French fries for dinner.
In families with thickets, sport is not exactly one of the favourite occupations, however, which also affects the majority of today's pupils - only 15 percent replied that their parents find themselves at least once a week for active exercise.
Survey among 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic being interviewed.
This was already the second year of the campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the Allgemeine Krankenkasse and the Gesellschaft Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from the 4th and 8th classes participated in the project.
Unhealthy food and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the alarming increase in the number of children with obesity or even obesity.
"Only half of the children surveyed, for example, said, five times a day to eat breakfast in the mode of second breakfast, lunch and dinner - one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet", is one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that also relative small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the pupils ’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families everyone will have breakfast on their own.
The worst thing was the finding that in every tenth family is not carved at all.
Breakfast is the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey showed, among other things, that in families of overweight children, unhealthy fries are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed are doing sports, only less than half of their parents do so - only 15 percent.
Get your own menu together
Another part of the survey made it possible for selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own menu from the possibilities offered by appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children prefer between 12 and 15 in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favourite dishes were many pastries, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonades", is emphasized in the final report to this survey.
At lunch, i.e. the main course, the pasta was just before poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get proper information.
"The results of the project indicate that the control group of those involved in the survey, who completed the questionnaire following the conclusion of the explanatory lecture" Obesity is not a coincidence ", has in many cases seen a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy nutrition."
This was remarkable, for example, in the sweet Limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also crossed poultry or fish as the main dish of the day and were ready to eat less dumplings or sweet food.
