V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree ride is caused by a series of completely avoidable, dilettantic errors for routine travel to the early shift.
Although it was possible to fulfil the ambitions to a large extent, what use is this already, if obviously nobody had desire to do a bit more.
Even before he came to the counter, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" awakened high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the already year-old game series "Need for Speed" to a new dimension again, and in the exemplary demonstration examples, he actually did not seem to be just one of many action championship racing games.
We were also curious about how the adapted passages fail, in which the main protagonist rises out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are used to with NFS, in the end, much is different than you had expected.
Sure - potentially there are quite decent arcade rounds, but overall the game is diminished by some superfluous mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So it is actually no longer a mistake, but rather a sign of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, history is introduced, the main character Jack has some personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, one sits on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
One has no moment the impression that game would always offer the same.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing moving about the world.
But the ride through the desert, through autumn scenery or high up through deeply snow-covered landscape seems visually very pleasant.
Every now and then untypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely limits the visibility.
In the mountains you have to be hellish, that you are not spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in a row.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And in addition the police interferes, which wants to massacre the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
This is more about some interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that in the game there are much less such passages than one would expect (in concrete terms only three).
Ultimately, this is more for the benefit of the matter, because this element has at least no chance of becoming boring - it belongs in the context of the above mentioned one of the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model steps in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means, from today's point of view, that it does not tear out trees, but on the other hand one could not claim that it would be bad.
Those looking for realistic simulations have to look around elsewhere.
But action-packed racing continues to do justice to the local driving model, although the competition could be better.
Until then, everything is in best order.
Real problems only appear after some time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
From a game of this kind it is hardly to be expected that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no impact on any object knowing how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: When you close overtaking or passing oncoming cars, you "strip" the other cars only lightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you get into the spin and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the cart goes straight to scrap.
Thanks to the rest of the system, it doesn ’ t matter, it ’ s annoying.
The rest arts are solved like this: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last clue of the track.
Only - in each race you have only five rests.
If you have exhausted them, everything starts from the front..
So the residual arts are rather something like an auxiliary, in the case that something does not succeed, but one should rather not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, not even the rest of the species helps, since nothing else helps to learn the critical section from the head.
Speaking unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to go through some curves in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit through.
Elsewhere, in the corresponding place, you always encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration, no matter whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or one minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you can see that the opponent passes two oncoming cars in front of a game, but until you arrive there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive them around or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you arrive there, everything is designed in such a way that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The opponents have further advantages.
In the whole game there are a few places where you are always overtaken at the same place by the same opponent and also here again without regard to the time.
The craziest thing is to finish the game on the long bridge, which you pass in opposite direction.
The opponent must overtake one here obviously on devil coming out.
And if he is in front of you, then he takes the view of course, so that you can drive your own car a few times there.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly forgets the joy of the game.
And this is a pity, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining overall and in places also so action-packed that one almost no longer knows where one stands the head.
And basically it doesn't matter what is "to blame" - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something quite different...
An unusual idea is also the change of cars in the course of the races.
One must not overlook the gas stations at the track, because it is precisely here that one can change the car, although in most cases the car is sufficient that one has just.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight motorways and exotic supercars for the technical trips, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of game history also goes the task of the game mode (challenges) - i.e. the races in the individual locations, which one knows from the history.
Here there are not only medals, but also points of experience for the own profile to win, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the history.
In order to reach the higher driver level, different items must be opened up: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is simultaneously associated with the online autolog function, which among other things compares the results obtained with those of other players and ensures further collective functions.
One of other incomprehensible carvers is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get by car into an U Bahn tunnel (for my sake), where you rest in the dark on the tracks long (for me).
On the speedometer numbers look between 150 a 200 km / h (my way), but there comes at once from behind an underground train and drives an uncompromising to scrap.
In our editors we will probably argue for a long time whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think us to be so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
This makes it all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
This concerns, in particular, accidents involving a greater number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound reproduction is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to address a wide and only possible scale of rather young audiences, a soundtrack a lá was created "by everyone something" - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? Feelings are rather mixed.
If the game were not diminished by the totally unnecessary mistakes mentioned above, we could have argued with the chest tone that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game seems somehow unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared that these mistakes with the power of airport lights in the eyes sting.
Concert of "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with singing ensembles of Charles University
The Festival Festa Academica now offers for the third time the combination of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution and this with music experience.
In the course of the festival, the twenty specialized and university choirs will introduce themselves.
The festival focuses on the two concerts that will take place on 17 November.
"Charles University has a large share of the festival."
"Among the participants is also represented the choir of the Pedagogical Faculty and the Faculty of Humanistic Studies, and in the festival committee there is also rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organizing team.
The highlight of the festival is the public concert of school choirs, which will take place on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice on 17 November from 2 pm.
The programme includes the composition of Karel Růžička, a renowned Czech jazz musician, "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evenings the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Studenty sametu) takes place in the gala rooms of the Folk House in Vinohrady, where also university choirs perform, and choirs of the Charles University are not excluded.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the World Student Day and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music at the highest level to the public and to promote the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organizer is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
Bohuslav Svoboda, the mayor of Prague and Václav Hampl, the rector of Charles University, took over the patronage of the entire event.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and in Pardubice.
In addition to festive concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, students ’ Happanings, Matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
