If one wanted to search for a suitable word that characterizes the strategy of IBM most accurately, then this would probably be the word "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, and it is known as a modern company, although a century has elapsed since its founding.
The basis for this longevity was laid by her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen. more
He already advocated the slogan that countless global problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a bit.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the trademark to which the life of the future giant was to take place (and at the same time the title of the company-internal magazine, which was already published by IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen ’ s thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for an entire century because it remained faithful to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around.
In the course of our first century, this allowed us to transform technologies, business and also society.
We hope to achieve even more in the next hundred years, "said Samuel J. Palmisano, today's director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Permeated system
Watson had social care for his employees already in the 1930s - in a similar way to the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: IBM's people had paid holidays as one of the first American employees, an insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a thoughtful remuneration system for the best innovators and traders.
The long-term relationships between IBM and its customers are just as sophisticated.
The company was brilliant in talent promotion right from the start - as one of the first companies in the world IBM lifted all discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy is also the current plan, which Palmisan will be replaced by a woman at the head of IBM next year - by Virginia Rometty.
This has been part of IBM for thirty years, so far it has taken the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years IBM has made so-called online brainstorming, from which many future strategies and innovations grow.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unshakable position in the business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
"From the outset, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," said Economist, the professor of Harvard Business School and the author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technologies," added George Colony of Consulting and Forrester Research.
As the company itself emphasises, it is a difference to be present on the market or to shape it directly through this presence.
IBM - in the states of its logo because of family called "Big Blue", has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies ever - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructures, hosting and consulting services in an incredible product range - from servers to nanotechnology.
IBM owns the most patents of all American technology companies and five of its employees have been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His most famous inventions include bank machines, credit cards, financial swap, barcode or even the floppy disk.
With about 220 billion dollars of stock market value (market capitalisation), IBM was the second largest technology company (right after Apple) this year, with Microsoft overtaking for the first time since 1996.
The view ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - unfortunately, for example, the attempt with the own operating system OS / 2, the online service Prodigy or also the computers IBM PC jr.
"Business is based on the forward movement, so you must not be emotionally bound to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
Therefore IBM has no problem to build its foundations on different platforms - and if they do not work to leave them again.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, who basically stands and falls with his operating system Windows.
Successful technologies
To a large extent, IBM ’ s profits involve services, software and hardware to one fifth each.
In 1990, hardware with a share of more than fifty percent was the strongest.
Since 2000, IBM has sold little profitable assets worth $15 billion, but at the same time it has invested $58 billion in purchasing future-oriented technologies.
In these investments IBM continues after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept over the world for the first time like a storm.
Here, too, IBM remained true to the legacy of its first chief Thomas J. Watson, who increased its investment volume in the midst of the great global economic crisis.
To date, IBM seems to survive today ’ s crisis without prejudice.
Since 2008, the value of IBM ’ s shares has increased by 120 percent like raketen-like and the company ’ s net profit is growing continuously.
The corporate slogan of IBM is: everything can be changed - only the values are not.
This is another reason why we can expect this flexible giant to overcome the next crisis.
IBM – History: From Cheese Cutter to Universal Flights
IBM (International Business Machines), founded in New York a hundred years ago, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
She took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was about a brand name for a branch office in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later company IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous engraved card clocks to register the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint became the architect of this new company, who also served as Chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader then even overshadowed the founders of IBM - based on Watson's ideas until today the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began to manufacture and distribute all kinds of machinery for the trade - from sausages and cheese-makers to cheeses.
In the first four decades in which Watson headed the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars, and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM started working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, engineers and computers from IBM helped NASA to direct flights to space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the series IBM System / 360.
A classic PC defining the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consulting section of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business with consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy IBM has paid off in the last three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the trading sector, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform to help retailers manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932 IBM founded a branch in the former Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, and here is also a top team of global researchers who deal with the technology of voice recognition.
