Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the former ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies sold mainly only journeys to the socialist countries of the East, while at that time only those who were chosen were allowed to travel to the West.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia embarked on a pro-Western course and therefore the trips to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (that is, Czechoslovakia) were allowed to travel freely within the socialist countries.
For example, if a ČSSR citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Back then, the travel agencies also offered travel to the West, but then they had to buy huge snakes or stay overnight in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the matter had not yet gone.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for a departure to the West - was given only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial means (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and data - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While by 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the nineties of the last century the foreign exchange obligation to the neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, which caused a huge wave of short visits especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not get enough of their journeys to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park while travelling to Paris, because who had already had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension.
At that time, a typical feature of Czechs' journeys abroad was a trunk packed with canned goods, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our level of living, and thus the average salaries, rose, which resulted in another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997 the travel agencies began to prepare regular trips by charter flights, whereby the air travel thanks to the possibility to negotiate quantity discounts, in comparison to the past unbelievably discounted.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, had already unpaid payments with all the advanced countries in the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvet" travel was in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was made - Thailand - thanks to the high demand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are served directly from the Czech Republic.
The 100 Tsd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States abolished visa requirements for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs spent for the first time more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 thousand CZK per capita for a single holiday stay including the cost at the resort.
The Annual General Meeting is to find a new chairman - again a patent threatens.
For almost five months, Czech football has not had a chairman, threatening that Ivan Hašek ’ s successor will not be known at the head of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) even after the extraordinary general meeting in Nymburk on Thursday.
To date, there is still no agreement on which electoral order is to be elected.
And without this, no vote is possible at all on the three potential successors.
Three interested parties want to manage Czech football - Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
In June, Hašek resigned from his position, calling on his colleagues to agree and find a strong personality who could lead football in the future.
Only - in the era after Hašek, the old squabbles broke out again between the two chambers, which cannot agree on a common candidate.
This was evident on September 16 when the new chairman was to be elected.
The delegates of the Annual General Meeting had come to the Popular House in the Smíchov district of Prague for free, because the hearing did not produce any results, and it was not just about the election itself.
One could not even agree on who is actually entitled to vote in the full collection - only the statutory representatives or also the officials equipped with an authorisation.
On this only point, agreement was reached at least in part, which was also supported by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, whose view that representation on a authoritative basis was not permissible.
However, the electoral disputes continue.
The Executive Committee, too, did not bring any more clarity into the matter, in its meetings - whether ordinary or extraordinary - in principle nothing else is on the agenda.
Even though the views on the election changed a few times - the neuralgic point remained the same.
The question is: how to proceed in the 3rd round to avoid a patent situation?
Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-chairmen of FAČR, who represents professional football in management, said: "The issue is whether to proceed in accordance with the statutes or whether to find a completely different model."
According to the statutory model, in the third round the candidate who receives the greater percentage support in the board for which he is running wins.
Moravia is supposedly prepared to respond to the compromise that the candidate who receives the higher number of votes from both chambers wins.
The Czech side, on the other hand, insists on the condition that the winner receives at least a two-thirds majority in this percentage counting.
"Then the two preliminary rounds no longer make any sense at all, this mode would question the entire two-chamber concept," Svoboda understands the Moravian side's objections, which would find it best not to bend the electoral order, but to vote according to valid statutes.
It is surprising that Tomáš Paclík agrees with this, even if it is clear that the statutory electoral system is most likely to meet Pelta by all candidates.
"My wish is that as much as possible be elected according to the statutes."
"In order not to devise any nonsensical alternatives, as at the last Annual General Meeting," said the owner (of the football club) Victoria Plzeň, who ran for the first time and distinguished himself from Pelta in his statements.
But Pelta remains optimistic.
In his opinion, the new chairman will be known in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates will also cooperate constructively in the future.
"The possible qualification of the national team for the football championship today would certainly contribute to calming the minds."
"When football first rides on the euphoric wave, then the willingness to cooperate is also greater," says the official from Jablonec, who brings the greatest experience of all three adepts and this at both professional and regional level.
Rajchl is more reserved.
"I hope for an agreement, but the situation is unfortunately ambivalent."
"This is not a matter between the people of Bohemia and Moravia, but there are certain efforts to" rectify "the rules for their own purposes."
"Therefore, a renewed blocking at the Annual General Meeting is not excluded."
"I hope, however, that common sense will ultimately win," Rajchl said.
Only - a lot of time to agree on all sides does not remain.
Some negotiations should supposedly take place directly in Montenegro, but who knows whether football generality will be complete until the qualifying game.
The charter plane, with which Dalibor Kučera and Rajchl were to fly to Podgorice, could not start in Prague in the morning because of a technical disturbance and so one searched feverishly for a replacement variant, how to bring a part of the executive committee nevertheless still to the place of the Barrage.
Finally, the ministerial meeting, which is supposed to take place on Wednesday, is probably crucial.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Physical Education, would have liked the divided parties within the country ’ s largest sports association to reach an agreement.
There is a lot at stake: state grants, the trustworthiness of Czech football and also the upcoming Annual General Meeting of ČSTV, which is to show the Czech sport the new direction after the financial problems of Sazka.
Paclík goes into the fight for the position of the chairman because he sees no suitable candidate
If Tomáš Paclík, head of the Pilsner football team, had been able to identify a strong candidate before the extraordinary general meeting who would have fulfilled all his ideas about the new chairman of the Football Association of the Czech Republic (FAČR), he would not have allowed himself to fight for this top position at all.
"If there were a good candidate, then I would fight for him and renounce the election."
"But in the current situation it was not possible to find such an adept," said Paclík ČTK.
The main reason for Paclík to go into a duel with Miroslav Pelta and Jindřich Rajchl is thus to prevent the alleged favourite of the election, Pelta, from reaching the top of the FAČR.
