"I spoke personally to some people in question."
"Hardly to believe that some people told me that they did not want to identify with Czech football at the moment.
"Such views would have liked to change," he said.
Most of all, Paclík allegedly disturbs Pelta's connection with the chairman of the Pilsner District Football Federation Roman Berbr, a man with a controversial reputation who is seen behind the scenes as a powerful lobbyist, with the ability to influence delegate votes at general meetings.
For Paclík, it is unacceptable for Pelta to hold the position of Chairman.
"In his victory today's condition would be preserved and in Czech football it would not go at all."
"The support of Berbr, a clever business man, would be twice as bad for football," Paclík stressed.
He also alludes to the fact that Pelta's name fell some time ago in connection with telephone interception for investigation in a corruption saffaire, from which Pelta emerged without punishment.
