Europe ’ s Most Beautiful Pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Splash pool in Ufo's optics, splendid pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience your blue miracle - and after a city tour or a hike, rest your tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness is the most beautiful in the water.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past year and a half, one of her luggage was not missing: her swimsuit.
Lying backwards on the water, she looked up in artfully designed domes, she swam marble to Putten, who waited for her on the edge of the pool, and marveled over meticulously restored Art Nouveau floating halls.
If she liked a bath, she took it up in her notebook - including interesting details about the building's construction and history.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architecture historian Meder in this way - and now introduces her in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historical bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore's concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries she led her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": Besides Germany, Austria and Switzerland she visited places in Italy, France, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and each one a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46 year-old German is a true bathing culture.
She doesn't have much to do with sport, says Meder - only in water is that different.
It is only annoying that swimming fans have to find their way away with blue tiles and chlorine stank, while joggers can breathe in the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird chirping in the park.
"One day I asked myself why swimming pools should always be so ugly," says the Meder living in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Splashes in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the spa factor in baths is so great because all senses are served, according to Meder.
And if the builders have given themselves trouble, swimming halls can be a real delight: "Instead of a floor one has a water surface in bathrooms."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but reflects the beauty of the whole building on the other."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" conveys information on the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
Remarkable specimens discovered the pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to splendid spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Spa in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a quaint karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc and Tapolca) and a thermal bath, whose basins are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: while you have the whole city in mind from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can observe the bustle on the ski piste.
The perhaps most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a ufo just reached in the Alps.
From three bowls open upwards it steams in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool the pool collector Meder rose the smell of chlorine into the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, in the Árpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it stinks so strongly after heating oil, which one hardly believes to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkaline hydrogen carbonate containing healing water, which is almost black and whose slick sticks to the skin as soon as you can slide into the pelvis - a wellness experience of the special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing places: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech town of Bad Luhatschowitz, she found a closed terrain.
The bathroom, designed by the architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902, has now been closed.
When Meder threw a glance through the weathered windows of the red-white-and-white Art Nouveau building, she saw weed growing between the tiles.
In contrast, one has counteracted the decay in an enchanting swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three construction phases have already passed this bath; one can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements, which date back to the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favourite swimming pool of the pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it originally came from the Black Forest.
"It is already a performance to merge so different styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace the dive in the thermal pool is apparently only secondary.
