21er House in Vienna
The Removed Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with ups, downs and happy ends: the Austrian world exhibition pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and closed.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition hall.
When modern post-war architecture is warmed by clear forms, glass halls, courageous swings and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Schwanzer is a striking and famous example for the 1958 Brüssler World Exhibition.
Schwanzers Pavillon was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built Austria ’ s pavilion at the next world exhibition.
In 1973 he finally became internationally famous with his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus an ingenious auxiliary building in Munich.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected, rebuilt after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna Southern Railway Station and opened a museum of the 20th century in 1962 - the "20er Haus" was called it.
But the building was neither spatial nor technical as a museum - no walls to hang art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001 the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein was the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein and Arco, art historian with a considerable career among others in the youth as figure skaters, later with Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, implemented the conversion emphatically with politicians and monument conservationists, they obtained public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
Besides contemporary art, the sculptor Fritz Wotruba ’ s works were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookshop were to be built, and an office building had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the execution Krischanitz was then the ideal occupation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrichs Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him a "tremendously important place" where he had "almost every weekend" seen the exhibitions.
He knew the draft of the Ur and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and lightness during its transfer to Vienna and its conversion.
There were far bigger problems with the current conversion: The building was "an energy spinner", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass fibre reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof replaced by special safety glass.
Refrigeration bridges have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two lower floors provided space for the new use, a lowered ditch of light between the house and the street ensures the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail-pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust protection.
And the cinema hall is exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the Monument Authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found, which is good and cheap and also liked the monument protection office", says Krischanitz and points to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop of the city's history".
Such an architecture stands "always in the wrong place" and nevertheless wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because there has been an urban development stroke of luck: the completely new "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings, is being built around the Swiss garden.
And another stroke of luck might happen: the 21er Haus could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporäre Kunsthalle, and as one hears, she already negotiates with the city for a neighbourly location in the Swiss garden.
