Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigrant opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who stood to have committed a shooting in Norway in July, in which 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent much time in front of his computer before his attack and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists supporting far-right groups on social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how to find it?
This is easy - you only have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it was not difficult to come to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the main author of a recent report by the DEMOS UK idea factory on digital populism in Europe.
Facebooks hiding personal data is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that the researchers simply have to use the advertising tool of the page to precisely determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett ’ s team found half a million supporters of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with adds, but instead of linking up with a new band or dietary product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking for their level of education, their attitude towards violence and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to consult more than 10,000 supporters of 14 extremely right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
"It is a quite new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online promoters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and annoy about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more rational, democratic, and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens. ”
DEMO ’ s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users, who add on average three content per day, Facebooks "Data Supernova" generates a research boom that has increased the number of scientific work with the name of this page in the title by almost 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study through this page people you normally don ’ t reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to question people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first and would never have allowed them access," says Bartlett.
"On Facebook, all this falls away - you go directly to them."
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and resolve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues has found that students who discussed their intoxication on Facebook are significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who were silent on this issue.
Moreno proposes that equal level students, for example residential consultants, monitor the site and help a student when posting too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it," said Dimitri Christakis, Morenos Ko's author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children who would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook is also constantly tapping the data of its own population.
The page ’ s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine ’ s Day, turnout in 2010 midterm elections, and a National Fortune Index (using primarily information that only Facebook has access to – masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data pit accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want it or not. To play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to share their personal information.
