How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that every day we lie between 10 and 200 times.
Many of these lies, however, are regarded as emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognising lies or "uncovering lies" is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game, such as charades, in which the aim is to call "Hab dich!", the imposition of a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities carrying out far-reaching research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look into your eyes.
They stutter, stammering, blush and do not always zappeln.
However, we must not conclude that these liars are difficult to uncover and to uncover.
An experienced deceiver of lies can penetrate to the truth by learning something about the structure of the assertion, the subtle expressions of the face, questions and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and constantly growing area of unction, and it is clear that the uncovering of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to cope with in our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning persons or negotiations or administration are part of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at judging other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions, and they feel intuitively how others perceive them.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people are more likely to lie than introverted people, that men are more likely to erect "self-oriented" lies than women, whose lies are more "oriented towards others" - as a rule they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less frequently than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of having appealed to that person.
How do you know if someone lies?
First of all, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluating changes.
Watch the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
They should know better when someone usually always tripples with the foot so that they do not wrongly accuse him when he tripples with the foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of striking verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not as evidence of an impregnation.
People who are deceiving might become stiff when trying to remember their story. Perhaps their feet point towards the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relaxation after the interview", this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
