Climate adversities slow down the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and who generates great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of climatic adversity, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of losses in agriculture, but also put tight limits on the growth of the national economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6% in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical reduction in agricultural development by 31.16%, which had a slowing effect on further economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has continuously increased unemployment in the Mexican state. Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, because from January to March 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa. That is 18,969 people more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year goes back to several factors. Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that the politics of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including liquidity losses on the market as a result of the cuts in funds adopted by legislation to combat money laundering in Congress, because it is not easy for those who are forbidden to accumulate dollars to let them work for themselves, invest them, or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined, on the one hand because of the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and seek work here, which increases unemployment," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if one takes into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38% of those employed in the country who work without paying into the social security coffers.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Agency) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September, much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decline of the ADI
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, the strongest decrease in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI amounted to 630 597 dollars from January to June, which corresponds to a shrinkage of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period last year.
For its part, the Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
In the light of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The National Congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but by November no positive impact of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be determined.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, Mario López Valdé ’ s first year of government made government incompetence obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), represented that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It has to be worked hard to regain the terrain lost this year and we have to make double efforts in 2012. The efforts of all, and especially the progress of the already well coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development more difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frosts. One of the most important effects is a slowed economy, which is not sufficiently on the move to generate an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will conclude the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Entrepreneurship Association) in Sinaloa, said that the state had to be led to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There is a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will guide the government ’ s efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas, economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas where one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively, and what I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
