In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the country government should not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration with general rules.
"Nor do I believe that if we were to do so, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected." She also pointed out that, for constitutional reasons, the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, because it directs national affairs.
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that has occurred in recent years around the world, and it causes better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the use of digitisation, which was a decision in the public interest that had not only technical aspects, "because it comprised economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "necessitated the action of the entire system, according to the principle of economic governance by the state they included a group of features that put the constitution into the hands of the central government."
It recalled that many countries around the world had already implemented the digital transition, namely the government, although they had highly specialised facilities.
One could not conclude that the government would intervene in the competences of the Congress by issuing the contested decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be respected, "she assured.
