In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles, reminded Zaragoza that, just last 9 November, the election office adopted a series of rules to harmonise local rules with the reforms of states in electoral matters.
It should be remembered that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force in this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Gazette within the time limits laid down for it with the argument to have neither objections against it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional action lodged by the local legislature and judged the State Representative's vote on the constitutional reforms to be "invalid and illegal" because he did not have the right to "decide or veto".
In an interview on the possibility of counting the votes, María de los Ángeles Llan stated that, thanks to the adoption of the directives by the Consejo General del IEM, there would now be the possibility that the local election authority could partially or completely count the ballots.
Under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted. The results of the minutes do not agree; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not available in the form of files or are not in the possession of the chairman of the election committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
Furthermore, the total counting of the fully filled ballots can take place if there is a difference between the presumed winner and the one who is in second place, which is equal or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition leader, who is the second of the named candidates.
The counting of votes may also take place in its entirety if, upon completion of the regular calculation, it is established that the difference between the presumed winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the electoral packages suspended from a partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is just under 0.16%, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
