The Prime Minister designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to present to him the new government, which will face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A communication from the Presidency Palace announced that the Monti appointed on Sunday would meet with the President of the Republic, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is assumed that he will present a cabinet composed by a majority of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the President the results of the talks with the political parties on the formation of a government.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," said the former EU commissioner to journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well defined", he added.
In less than three days, Monti has managed to form a government, which is much less time than normal. Meanwhile, Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has driven the cost of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by the former EU commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package called for by euro-policymakers to regain the stiff confidence in Italy.
The pressure on Monti was intensified by the fluctuating market situation, as a result of which Italian government bonds were burdened with 7% interest for 10 years, corresponding to the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European rescue umbrella.
