Fujimori returned to hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, informed his family doctor.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is 25 years in prison for violating human rights during his reign (1990 – 2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which operates four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a congress member and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas Peruvian hospital to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower body.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons. Nevertheless, he did not wish this because he considered him innocent.
He was operated four times on tongue cancer and has lost 18 kilos of weight. In addition, other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood circulation problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squadron of the Peruvian army, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday. According to the Uruguayan president, this will be the culmination of his booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries", announced the presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica seeks Calderón ’ s support for the incident with France, when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a tax paradise list at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that still appear as tax havens. Uruguay rejected this declaration and asked his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chaired by the G20 since November, a group consisting of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world. Since January of this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid duplication with the South American country.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the concretization of agreements for the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which does not include all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
There has been a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay at business level since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The bearded installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for the rescue of Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser for 25 years, but never until now in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he fights for the love of the girl in Stereo.
The game, which comes this month to the shop counters all over the world, has been tailored from the very beginning to the features of the Nintende 3DS portable console, which can be played three-dimensionally without special glasses.
"Mario is the figure who has to say how stereoscopy works without glasses," said Omar Álvarez, the person in charge of the Nintendo press in Spain, at the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez explained that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first video game from Nintendo that has been developed for this console from the very beginning", because so far successful articles like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" have been adaptations of already existing titles.
The speaker of Nintendo underlined that although it is three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows a fast, fluid game.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: the first part is "light" to capture the less shocked users.
Afterwards, the experts can turn a "second round" over the different game levels, which are becoming more and more difficult.
In addition, users can choose between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action in real time. However, in order to overcome the obstacles without becoming victims of the "optical effects", three dimensions must always be played.
This excursion of Super Mario into the three-dimensional world also means the return of the figure to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo winks towards the fans of the saga and repeats the recipe for success of the last editions: The bearded installer has to overcome platforms cluttered with dangers in order to free Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters news about the movements, the environment, the disguises and the enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
