Trinijove has helped 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organisation was established to avoid the marginalisation of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of the social assistance organisation Trinijove have led to important results: in this quarter century, 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion were supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
There are more than a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event was held yesterday in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people took part.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the district of Trinitat Vella with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems threatened by the risk of marginality.
At yesterday ’ s celebration in Sant Andreu, numerous officials from institutions and institutions who worked with the association during these 25 years participated.
The participation of political representatives of different directions at election times demonstrated the impartiality of the work carried out by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol attended the celebrations of former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and currently left the green city council Ricard Goma.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was visited by Josep Lluís Cleries, the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family Affairs, and Jaume Lanaspa, the Director General of Social Services at the La Caixa Savings Bank.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was launched in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far is "a good basis".
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is a model that knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the association and the work it does," he explained.
Occupied house where giant parties were held was cleared
The owners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on the street Balmes No. 51 (Barcelona).
The twelve squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without any resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of house No. 51 on the street Balmes have come to an end.
Yesterday at noon twelve people voluntarily left the building, which they had illegally occupied and in which they had organized huge festivals, which had driven the neighborhood to despair. The eviction took place on a judicial order without any police intervention.
After the clearing, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on access will be controlled", confirmed the house manager.
The squatters who had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the others were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply. They also painted the walls and left all kinds of garbage, especially cans with alcoholic beverages.
In the three lower floors huge parties were celebrated, which lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had declined by 80% since the start of the squatting.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the squatters did their unfair competition because they sold the drinks to three euros, while they cost 10 euros in the discotheque.
Furthermore, the owner of the leisure area had been reported by the neighbors for resting, while according to her statement the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the squatters and in particular from the guests of the festivals that were organized there, and which according to the statements of the angry neighbors became more and more in the last weeks.
The manager of the discotheque explained that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (urban police) also confirmed that in the past few weeks she had received more complaints from her neighbours.
The chairman of the PP (Partido Popular) in the Barcelona City Council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, called last week for the building to be cleaned up without delay and to deal with the problems of civil coexistence and the coming down of the district.
He explained that before the summer only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that the squatters had penetrated in the last few months into all floors of the building and almost all apartments. In some cases even thefts had occurred.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to intervene against the asocial actions in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was cleared by the Catalan police.
At 3.30 p.m., the police approached Montral Street No. 35 after receiving a call from a neighbor who had watched four people penetrating the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
