Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane accident in which the Secretary of State Francisco Blake and another seven people were killed.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communication and Transport in Mexico) informed that the findings of the investigation on the accident, in which the Secretary of State Francisco Blake Mora and another seven people were killed, indicate that the helicopter, with its entire intact structure, has collided directly against the ground without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, said that the pilot had confirmed before the start that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wings had contact with trees at a height of 25 metres, with the helicopter losing the fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why he fulfilled all the requirements for the transport of the personnel.
Furthermore, he said that no helicopter parts were found in the investigations in the field where the machine had come down.
"In the search no aircraft parts were found in other places, the surcharge concerned the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it fulfilled all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a matter of priority to obtain the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even one year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Relief Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter from Estado Mayor Presidencial had flown at an extra speed and had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information strengthens the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the collision."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of the visual flight. This means that the crew should have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at take-off. During the onward flight towards the border area between Mexico and the Mexico State, some low hanging clouds rose.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca valley because of the clouds.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter agree. Possibly, before the impact, there was neither a loss of control over the plane nor a deviation from the flight route.
Scattering of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available up to now indicates that the helicopter had hit from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggest that the helicopter had hit the ground with its intact structure.
No indications of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer at the accident site do not indicate fire or explosion.
The latest findings indicate several ground contacts.
During the on-site investigations aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has an incline of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a minuscule search in an area that went beyond the closed off area at the accident site, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, which reinforces the assumption that the unharmed aircraft structure had collided against the ground.
MSS announces a research protocol on finding the gene for obesity
The Mexican Social Security Agency is conducting a research project to locate the obesity gene in children and adolescents supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Security Agency of Mexico) announced that it is conducting a research project on the discovery of the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth", with which the genetic markers are to be found in combination with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, stated that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the IMSS sports fields in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are carried out every Saturday from 8.00 am.
He stressed that the investigation started on the Cuauhtémoc sports field (in the west of the state of México) and continued on the Nezahualcóyolt sports field (in the east of the state of México) since 8 October.
When the target of 500 to 600 investigators is reached, the study is continued on the Independencia sports field (in the south of the capital district) and completed on that of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He said that the aim of the study was to get to know the factors and role of genetics in connection with the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the global day of diabetes, he said that it was intended that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 should fill in nutritional questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and family disease history to control risk factors that may result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He also pointed out that on the above-mentioned Saturdays the examiners were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood values such as the glucose level, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (attempt to identify genes related to childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be carried out on the occasion of health workers' concerns about the alarming increase in weight of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years the proportion of obese boys has increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. Also the overweight has increased dramatically," stressed the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the Mexican population differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that an (e) Mexican (in) is, on average, 65 per cent, Indian American, 30 per cent European, and 5 per cent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
More generally, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the surplus of energy (calories) taken from us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants would be in a comprehensive examination of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of overweight or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin wrinkles in the neck and the inner arm (acanthosis) indicating the probability of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the prestage.
All information is treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. Doctors explain all measurement results to the parents and suggest changes to the lifestyle that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the television and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. an increased consumption of sugared beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake as well as the genetics, which is to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM, develops polymers modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
It would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 potholes if the rainy season broke out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (urban area of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning and assuring that if the layout and maintenance of the asphalt covering were to be appropriate, the number of potholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Potholes from a Technical Perspective", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops asphalt modified with polymers in order to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, which, however, has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with an extremely hot climate, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called Malthene. Together they lend the road surface its characteristic visceral behavior.
Countable behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180 ° C, at 120 ° C it is very viscous and at 50 ° C almost firm, while at very low temperatures it becomes fragile.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico ’ s city had a flexible surface composed of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Between the top layers there is a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalt and then solidified stones.
Every single stone of this layer of wear was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he said, "one last layer is laid out, the so-called supporting layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle grips, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
The one that receives and distributes most of the forces of this road surface also needs an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water, "he said," because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets damp, water penetrates the layer and only occurs difficult again. That causes a softening of all layers of the road covering and consequently the occurrence of potholes.
When a punch hole arises, "he said," the top layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. However, the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained in the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs. "
The member of the National Research System of Mexico (Sistema Nacional de Investigadores) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be relative to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there were still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be easily repaired without using high temperatures.
