Thus was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4, a Lophoscopist of the Investigation Unit of the Prosecutor ’ s Office (CTI) of Cali, as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia – Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia), went in: “Alfonso Cano ” by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven Lophoscopists in the CTI department, Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years, was on call this week.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities in Chocó, where he often had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completion of the necessary courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin exposed to friction, i.e. the palm and foot surfaces.
In the week of operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something great awaited him.
Friday night he flew by helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he was to identify two corpses, and that there was suspicion that one could be that of the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world. Therefore, he was to take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he reached the place where the corpse was located with the investigator, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, because it did not resemble the figures he had seen in the mass media in the slightest.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, wore no glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints do not lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a plant cell and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those on the print sheet.
He had seen correctly: it was "Alfonso Cano".
The same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for telling the Defense Minister, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was actually the head of the FARC.
In search of traces
For a Daktyloskopen from Sijín in Cali, the appreciation given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the operation against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Daktyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murder and predators and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When arrested, many criminals file false identity documents or they have none.
We take the fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house in case of theft, because the thief had supported himself exactly at this point with his hand when he pulled out a safe filled with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we could take the impression of the whole hand and identify the criminal who had participated in several thefts," he remembered.
Using the fingerprints, murder suspects can also be relieved or burdened.
Recently a dead man was found surrounded by schnapps bottles.
In the investigation it was assumed that a family member could be suspicious of action, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle agreed.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is nevertheless linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A Daktyloscopist of the CTI explained that "fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents would be taken from the object."
When they appear, a plant cell or tape is used to carry them.
Afterwards the impressions are sent to the Asif, that is the criminal database, or to the personal stand office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identification documents," explained the expert of the CTI.
He said that not everything was as it was shown in the TV series SCI.
Just as not all gold is, what shines, neither is everything you touch, a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
