Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an opportunity to vote, to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it examines the whole of the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts and rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is pushing forward a doubling of electricity demand by the year 2050, not to have to give up an enormous proportion of the world ’ s population on a vital element.
At the same time, we must alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue producing electricity, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which subordinates its decision to the need to find a substitution source, nor in Switzerland, which only intends to build nuclear power stations of the last generation.
Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
For their part, after Fukushima, the United States decided to join its park by reinstating the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model, which is based on renewable energy sources, is occasionally presented as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence on Russia, in particular, due to increased reliance on import gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power stations.
The whole of these unpleasant effects will become apparent within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives rise to reflection.
Denmark, on the one hand, is a European leader in terms of wind energy, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, and, on the other hand, is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the energy price in the globalised economy plays a key role in competitiveness and a national stability of industry, French companies have an advantage because of the most favourable electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a strong increase in energy prices, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of the French are not prepared to pay, as they show resistance to the principle of this source of energy.
Let us bear in mind that our country ’ s energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
If France took the decision to withdraw from nuclear power, a large proportion of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual EUR 6 billion in capital goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would assign an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of his producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation one has to admit that there is just as little miracle agent for generating electricity as there is a devil's work.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent controls in existing plants, such as the Flamanville site.
Their work teams, which have made a name for themselves due to their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the safety concept.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, namely in Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions; so it proceeded without consequences for humans and environment.
In Chernobyl the drama was summoned by reactor construction as well as indefinable human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn its lessons from this accident, as it had done after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and constructors of nuclear power plants, the EPR is a design that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power station, a stop at Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competitors of Areva and EDF by allowing them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is indispensable and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and party maneuvers to dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy was criticized from many angles - overload of police, judicial and administrative bodies on the basis of a policy subjected to the figures, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had called itself.
