But this policy has rarely been analysed from the economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right the tone of Jacques Chirac was struck, who in 1976 declared that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", from the left by Michel Rocard, who in 1990 had stated that France "could not absorb all the world's poverty".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided in 2005 from both the right and the left.
Both camps saw immigrants as a burden for the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that immigrants are willing to admit.
Francois Hollande ’ s programme is limited to banalities that point out that partnership development allows us to solve our “migration problems ”.
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on elections, but it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent work summarising the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the flood of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in the immigration countries.
Restricting immigration would defuse growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they are threatening to substitute the local workers, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are, in reality, much more complementary than domestic wage workers, as they focus on occupations in sectors that are unemployed in terms of workplace technology.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic wage workers, and the more qualified immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not adapted to the labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a lack of anaesthetists, this complementarity also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market situation between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants will bring about an inclusive, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas created by immigrants is beneficial as well as economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, in European countries on average around 1% of the total budget.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 contributes a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget on average over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the lack of intersections "with the teeth" at the beginning of his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which were supposed to deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
