"Contactless" smart cards become the general good
The World Fair for Chip Cards opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris with an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 was supposed to end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM cards and telephone), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment is the contactless technology, which enables payments in public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold one year earlier, 460 million contactless smart cards should be sold worldwide this year!
Their market share should increase further in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent more than 10% of the global chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in terms of contactless payment after having been lagging behind for a long time in the Asia Pacific region.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept them.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards were disseminated.
However, consumer markets are steaming.
Carrefour has therefore issued this year 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCards.
In order to move to higher speed, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
"In future, two major French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically hand over their customers bank cards equipped with a contactless chip," announces Gérard Nébouy, Director General of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only a first stage on the way to the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
A tiny percentage of devices has so far been equipped with the Near Field Communication (NFC) technology necessary for carrying out these transactions.
"They are in default".
"But they should at least experience a real upward development next year."
"We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
But the banks take initiative.
The Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale, too, announced yesterday that it would prepare the market launch of an offer that would enable its customers to make contactless payments by mobile phone.
