Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, was put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendour and gloria.
More than 500 invited guests, including four Heads of State and Government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline on the Baltic Sea coast last Tuesday under orchestral sound and with a gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart Mark Rutte from the Netherlands symbolically jointly rotated the valve that transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline is to supply 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length linking the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg's Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline allowing a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to total French consumption, is due to be completed by the end of 2012.
And one already lets the eventuality of the construction of a third line echo itself.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
In fact, the Northern Stream pipeline will allow direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any route by land through third countries (Poland or Ukraine).
That is why these two countries are losing a little of their power: they are now finding it more difficult to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most heavily engaged in the debate, was not shy away from comparing the Northern Stream pipeline with a "new German pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of Poland's occupation in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, is at the expense of de-vigorating European energy, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years, Russia has managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas resources are running out.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us in an organic way," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are also important from the political and economic point of view.
All of this explains the broad smile of Gazprom ’ s numerous gas supply managers in Lubmin.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipeline consists of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at a depth of about 200 m.
During their construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be evaded.
"Approximately hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long serpent of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither by valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project managers have refrained from doing so, as the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state-owned company permanently settling at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas transmission in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
This case, however, is considered to be unlikely by the designers, as the weld seams were estimated to be resistant to one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes by a seagoing vessel, and by an apparatus which circulates inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is inserted into the inside of the pipe and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides accurate information on any metal deformation upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (15.5% each), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a business group called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, on an extendable twenty year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the actual volume of gas transported is," Jens Müller specified.
The financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are certain to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone carries the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline appears on a sandy coastline with pine forests near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas exit gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other indicators of the incoming gas before it is transmitted to the German gas pipeline.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
At full capacity, these would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
