Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a purposeful public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice the average average: 19% against 9% unemployment of the total population.
Discouraging?
"No, said Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, who is organizing the" Week of Work for the Disabled. "
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not double, but triple."
"Nevertheless, a great deal remains to be done."
It must be said, however, that many obstacles remain for the disabled unemployed before they get a job.
It is more common for older people: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% of them have no Abitur and only 10,000 disabled people are among the 2.3 million students with higher education qualifications.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled compared to 38% for the overall average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it more difficult to re-enter the labour market and that form the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
Remains the unspoken, the mental attitudes, which certainly but slowly develop.
A study carried out in April by the IMS association Entreprendre for the magazine La Cité indicated that the managers questioned had "a weak level of knowledge about disabled persons", which "is over-represented" by persons in wheelchairs, psychologically or intellectually minors ".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers, which was laid down in a law of 1987.
These last figures from 2008 indicate a quotient of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organisation responsible for collecting contributions from companies that violate this law.
The proof is that the number of "fees paid" establishments has decreased, as has the amount of amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, put strong pressure on companies, said Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the premises employ disabled persons between 20 and 49 employees, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
